    question: "What is tramp oil in machining coolant?",
    answer: "Tramp oil is hydraulic fluid, slideway oil, and spindle oil that leaks from machine tool systems into the coolant sump. Unlike cutting oil (which is water-soluble coolant concentrate), tramp oil is immiscible with water. It floats on the sump surface, fosters bacterial growth, causes dermatitis, and degrades coolant performance."
  },
  {
    question: "How does a centrifuge remove tramp oil from coolant?",
    answer: "A disc stack centrifuge spins the coolant at 7,000+ Gs, which forces the denser water and fines outward and allows the lighter tramp oil to migrate inward to a separate discharge port. The cleaned coolant returns to the sump continuously, with solids automatically ejected every 10&ndash;60 minutes."
  },
  {
    question: "What size centrifuge do I need for tramp oil removal?",
    answer: "Sizing depends on sump volume and machine count. A typical rule is to turn over the full sump volume every 1&ndash;2 hours. For a 500-gallon sump, a DMPX-010 (7 GPM) provides a 70-minute turnover. For larger central sump systems (2,000+ gallons), a DMPX-028 (20&ndash;26 GPM) or DMPX-042 (32&ndash;47 GPM) is more appropriate."
  },
  {
    question: "What is the ROI of a tramp oil centrifuge?",
    answer: "Typical payback is 12&ndash;24 months. Savings come from reduced coolant replacement, lower waste disposal costs, extended tool life (15&ndash;30% improvement is common), fewer bacterial treatment chemicals, and reduced machine maintenance. Contact Dolphin Centrifuge for a facility-specific ROI analysis."
  }
