  relatedApplications={relatedApplications}
  relatedProducts={relatedProducts}
>

  <div class="bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6 not-prose">
    <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge supplies disc stack centrifuge systems for tramp oil removal from metalworking coolant sumps. Operating at 7,000+ Gs, these self-cleaning separators continuously remove hydraulic and slideway oils while leaving water-soluble coolant intact.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- What Is Tramp Oil -->
  <h2 id="what-is-tramp-oil">What Is Tramp Oil?</h2>

  <div class="not-prose flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-start my-6">
    <div>
      <img
        src="/images/tramp-oil-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-WSPX-307-Water-Based-Coolant-Centrifuge.webp"
        alt="Alfa Laval WSPX-307 Water-Based Coolant Centrifuge for tramp oil separation"
        width="750"
        height="505"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-sm max-w-xs md:max-w-sm"
      />
    </div>
    <div class="flex-1">
      <p class="text-text leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Tramp oil is petroleum-based lubricant that enters a metalworking coolant sump from sources other than the coolant itself. Unlike the water-soluble coolant concentrate intentionally mixed into the sump, tramp oil is an uninvited contaminant originating from:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2 text-text-light">
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Machine tool lubrication systems:</strong> Hydraulic oil, slideway oil, and spindle lubricants leak from machine tool components directly into the coolant sump over time. Even a well-maintained machine tool may contribute 1&ndash;5 liters of tramp oil per week.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Parts transport oils:</strong> Residual machining oils from incoming workpieces drip into the coolant as parts are machined.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Rust preventive oils:</strong> Anti-corrosion coatings applied to incoming material or fixtures dissolve partially into the coolant.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Forklift and overhead crane drips:</strong> In facilities with busy material handling operations, petroleum drips reach coolant sumps.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    In a typical machining facility, an active coolant sump accumulates tramp oil at 0.5&ndash;3% of sump volume per week. A 2,000-liter sump may be gaining 10&ndash;60 liters of tramp oil per week &mdash; enough to cause serious contamination problems within days to weeks if not removed.
  </p>

  <!-- Why It Must Be Removed -->
  <h2 id="why-remove">Why Tramp Oil Must Be Removed</h2>

  <p>
    Tramp oil is more than an aesthetic problem. Its presence in the coolant system causes a cascade of degradation effects:
  </p>

  <h3>Bacterial Growth and Coolant Degradation</h3>
  <p>
    Tramp oil coats the surface of the coolant sump with an oxygen-limiting film. Beneath this film, anaerobic bacteria thrive &mdash; breaking down the coolant's biocide package, consuming emulsifiers, and producing sulfurous compounds that cause the characteristic rotten-egg smell of a failed coolant. A sump with high tramp oil content may require complete dump-and-recharge every 2&ndash;4 weeks rather than every 6&ndash;12 months, representing enormous coolant cost and disposal expense.
  </p>

  <h3>Tool Wear and Surface Finish Degradation</h3>
  <p>
    Effective coolant must reach the cutting zone as a uniform emulsion. Tramp oil disrupts the emulsion stability, causing inconsistent tool lubrication and cooling. The result is accelerated tool wear, shorter tool life, and degraded surface finish quality &mdash; all directly impacting production cost and reject rates.
  </p>

  <h3>Foam Generation</h3>
  <p>
    Tramp oil &mdash; particularly hydraulic oil &mdash; reacts with coolant emulsifiers to generate persistent foam. Foam reduces coolant flow, causes pump cavitation, makes sump level monitoring unreliable, and creates housekeeping problems as foam overflows sumps.
  </p>

  <h3>Worker Health Hazards</h3>
  <p>
    Tramp oil in coolant aerosol (mist) is a recognized occupational health hazard. The fine oil droplets generated during high-speed machining operations carry bacteria and irritating compounds that cause dermatitis and respiratory irritation. NIOSH and OSHA have established coolant mist exposure limits specifically because of this risk. Removing tramp oil significantly reduces mist toxicity.
  </p>

  <h3>Machine Staining and Corrosion</h3>
  <p>
    Tramp-oil-contaminated coolant loses its rust inhibitor effectiveness &mdash; leading to surface staining on machined parts and corrosion on machine tool surfaces. Rework and part rejection costs from corrosion-related issues can be significant.
  </p>

  <!-- How a Disc Centrifuge Removes It -->
  <h2 id="how-centrifuge-removes">How a Disc Centrifuge Removes Tramp Oil</h2>

  <div class="not-prose flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-start my-6">
    <div>
      <img
        src="/images/tramp-oil-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-WSPX303-Coolant-Centrifuge.webp"
        alt="Machine coolant centrifuge for tramp oil removal - WSPX303 model"
        width="400"
        height="400"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-sm max-w-xs"
      />
    </div>
    <div class="flex-1">
      <p class="text-text leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Tramp oil separation is an ideal application for <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-efficiency/" class="text-navy font-semibold hover:text-gold transition-colors">disc centrifuge technology</a> because the separation challenge is purely a density difference between two liquids &mdash; exactly what disc centrifuges are engineered to exploit.
      </p>
      <p class="text-text leading-relaxed">
        Petroleum-based tramp oils have specific gravities of approximately 0.85&ndash;0.90 g/cm&sup3;. Metalworking coolant (water-based emulsion at typical concentrations) has a specific gravity of approximately 0.99&ndash;1.00 g/cm&sup3;. This density difference of 0.09&ndash;0.15 g/cm&sup3; is sufficient for disc centrifuge separation at 6,000&ndash;9,000&times; gravity.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>The separation process:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Contaminated coolant is pumped from the sump to the centrifuge feed inlet at a controlled flow rate.</li>
    <li>Inside the rotating disc stack, the density difference between tramp oil and coolant is amplified by centrifugal force. Coolant (denser) moves outward; tramp oil (lighter) concentrates in the inner zone.</li>
    <li>Clarified coolant exits through the light phase outlet &mdash; in this application, the coolant is the &ldquo;heavy&rdquo; phase being clarified of even lighter tramp oil.</li>
    <li>Concentrated tramp oil accumulates and is continuously discharged through the heavy-phase (actually light-density) outlet or via periodic bowl discharge.</li>
    <li>Fine metal swarf particles present in the coolant are simultaneously removed as solids, accumulating in the bowl sludge space and discharged periodically.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The result is coolant returning to the sump with tramp oil content reduced to below 0.1% &mdash; essentially free of tramp oil contamination on a continuous basis.
  </p>

  <!-- Comparison to Alternatives -->
  <h2 id="comparison">Comparison to Skimmers and Coalescers</h2>

  <div class="not-prose flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-start my-6">
    <div>
      <img
        src="/images/tramp-oil-centrifuge/Alfa-Laval-WSPX-307-Coolant-Centrifuge-600.webp"
        alt="Alfa Laval WSPX-307 coolant centrifuge compared to conventional tramp oil removal methods"
        width="600"
        height="423"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-sm max-w-xs md:max-w-sm"
      />
    </div>
    <div class="flex-1">
      <p class="text-text leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Tramp oil skimmers and gravity coalescers are simpler and less expensive than centrifuges, but they have significant limitations:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-2 text-text-light">
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Belt/disk skimmers:</strong> Remove only the free-floating surface layer of tramp oil. Emulsified or finely dispersed tramp oil &mdash; which accounts for most of the contamination in an active sump &mdash; passes through completely untouched. Effectiveness: typically 20&ndash;40% tramp oil reduction.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Gravity coalescers:</strong> Use media to coalesce small oil droplets into larger ones that float to the surface for skimming. More effective than skimmers alone, but still limited to droplets larger than approximately 50&ndash;100 microns. Effectiveness: typically 40&ndash;70% tramp oil reduction.</li>
        <li><strong class="text-navy">Disc centrifuge:</strong> Operates at 6,000&ndash;10,000&times; gravity, separating oil droplets down to 1&ndash;2 micron size. Removes both free and emulsified tramp oil simultaneously. Also removes fine metal fines as a bonus. Effectiveness: typically 90&ndash;99%+ tramp oil reduction.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    For sumps where tramp oil control is critical to coolant life and part quality, the centrifuge delivers results that skimmers and coalescers simply cannot match.
  </p>

  <!-- Flow Rates and Sizing -->
  <h2 id="sizing">Flow Rates and Centrifuge Sizing</h2>

  <p>
    Sizing a tramp oil centrifuge for a coolant sump application requires two inputs: the sump volume and the tramp oil ingress rate.
  </p>
  <p>
    As a general rule, the centrifuge should be capable of processing the entire sump volume in 4&ndash;8 hours during continuous operation. This &ldquo;turnover time&rdquo; ensures that tramp oil entering the sump is captured before it builds to damaging concentrations.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Small sump (500&ndash;2,000 L):</strong> 200&ndash;500 L/hour centrifuge capacity typically sufficient</li>
    <li><strong>Medium sump (2,000&ndash;10,000 L):</strong> 1,000&ndash;2,500 L/hour</li>
    <li><strong>Large central sump or multiple machines (10,000&ndash;50,000 L):</strong> 3,000&ndash;10,000+ L/hour; may use multiple centrifuges or a larger industrial model</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For <a href="/machine-coolant-centrifuge/">machine coolant centrifuge</a> and <a href="/cutting-oil-centrifuge/">cutting oil centrifuge</a> applications, the same sizing logic applies with the separation parameters adjusted for the specific coolant and oil types involved. See also our guide on <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-lubrication/">disc stack centrifuge lubrication</a> for maintenance best practices.
  </p>

  <!-- ROI -->
  <h2 id="roi">ROI of Tramp Oil Removal</h2>

  <p>
    The return on investment for a tramp oil centrifuge is typically faster than most capital equipment purchases. The savings come from multiple sources simultaneously:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Coolant extension:</strong> Sumps contaminated with tramp oil require dump-and-recharge every 2&ndash;8 weeks. Clean sumps typically run 6&ndash;18 months. For a 5,000-liter sump with coolant cost of $20/liter, avoiding even two extra dump cycles per year saves $200,000 annually.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduced coolant concentrate usage:</strong> Bacteria-degraded coolant loses concentration faster, requiring more frequent concentrate additions. Removing tramp oil stabilizes coolant concentration and reduces concentrate consumption 20&ndash;40%.</li>
    <li><strong>Waste disposal cost reduction:</strong> Spent coolant is regulated waste with disposal costs of $0.20&ndash;$0.80 per liter. Halving the frequency of sump dumps halves the disposal cost.</li>
    <li><strong>Tool life improvement:</strong> Facilities consistently report 15&ndash;30% improvement in tool life after implementing effective tramp oil removal, from restored coolant lubrication and cooling performance.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduced maintenance and downtime:</strong> Cleaner sumps mean fewer pump clogs, cleaner filters, and less machine maintenance related to coolant degradation.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Contact Dolphin Centrifuge to discuss a specific ROI analysis for your facility &mdash; the numbers are often compelling enough to justify expedited purchase approval.
  </p>
  <p>
    Ready to discuss tramp oil removal for your facility? Contact Dolphin Centrifuge at <a href="tel:+12485222573">(248) 522-2573</a> or <a href="mailto:sales@dolphincentrifuge.com">sales@dolphincentrifuge.com</a>. You can also explore our <a href="/industrial-centrifuge-sample-testing/">free sample testing service</a> to verify separation performance before purchasing.
  </p>

  <!-- FAQ -->
